# gen134 (L16/L19): BRANCHING abduction — enumerating the hypothesis space. When
# several rules conclude the same goal, abduction reports every ALTERNATIVE
# explanation, not just the first. Closes the open edge gen131/132 flagged. The
# alternatives are read from the real rule set (kb_rules_for_head /
# kb_nth_rule_body_preds), each naming only its own missing premises.

# Two independent rules conclude pet: cat -> pet and dog -> pet.
> every cat is a pet
< Learned rule: pet(X) :- cat(X).
> every dog is a pet
< Learned rule: pet(X) :- dog(X).
> is rex a pet?
< No.

# Abduction now offers BOTH ways — the disjunctive hypothesis space.
> what would make rex a pet?
< There's more than one way: either rex is a cat, or rex is a dog — any one would make rex a pet.
> why isn't rex a pet?
< rex is not a pet because every alternative is blocked: cat -> pet needs rex is a cat; dog -> pet needs rex is a dog.

# gen137 stress probe: ten independent alternatives, all blocked.
> every alpha is a signal
< Learned rule: signal(X) :- alpha(X).
> every beta is a signal
< Learned rule: signal(X) :- beta(X).
> every gamma is a signal
< Learned rule: signal(X) :- gamma(X).
> every delta is a signal
< Learned rule: signal(X) :- delta(X).
> every epsilon is a signal
< Learned rule: signal(X) :- epsilon(X).
> every zeta is a signal
< Learned rule: signal(X) :- zeta(X).
> every eta is a signal
< Learned rule: signal(X) :- eta(X).
> every theta is a signal
< Learned rule: signal(X) :- theta(X).
> every iota is a signal
< Learned rule: signal(X) :- iota(X).
> every kappa is a signal
< Learned rule: signal(X) :- kappa(X).
> why isn't zed a signal?
< zed is not a signal because every alternative is blocked: alpha -> signal needs zed is a alpha; beta -> signal needs zed is a beta; gamma -> signal needs zed is a gamma; delta -> signal needs zed is a delta; epsilon -> signal needs zed is a epsilon; zeta -> signal needs zed is a zeta; eta -> signal needs zed is a eta; theta -> signal needs zed is a theta; iota -> signal needs zed is a iota; kappa -> signal needs zed is a kappa.

# gen138: optimal abduction chooses the lowest-cost way across alternatives.
> every prepared dog is a champion
< Learned rule: champion(X) :- prepared(X), dog(X).
> every royal vip is a champion
< Learned rule: champion(X) :- royal(X), vip(X).
> rex is a dog
< Learned: dog(rex). Now rex is a pet after all.
> what is the easiest way to make rex a champion?
< The easiest way is to tell me that rex is a prepared — 1 missing premise via prepared and dog -> champion.
> try the easiest way to make rex a champion
< Hypothetically adding rex is a prepared makes rex a champion: champion(rex) because prepared(rex) and dog(rex). I restored the KB after the simulation.
> is rex a champion?
< No.


# gen138 stress probe: ten alternatives; the best one is last and partly satisfied.
> every alpha beta gamma is a marker
< Learned rule: marker(X) :- alpha(X), beta(X), gamma(X).
> every delta epsilon zeta is a marker
< Learned rule: marker(X) :- delta(X), epsilon(X), zeta(X).
> every eta theta iota is a marker
< Learned rule: marker(X) :- eta(X), theta(X), iota(X).
> every kappa lambda mu is a marker
< Learned rule: marker(X) :- kappa(X), lambda(X), mu(X).
> every nu xi omicron is a marker
< Learned rule: marker(X) :- nu(X), xi(X), omicron(X).
> every pi rho sigma is a marker
< Learned rule: marker(X) :- pi(X), rho(X), sigma(X).
> every tau upsilon phi is a marker
< Learned rule: marker(X) :- tau(X), upsilon(X), phi(X).
> every xchi psi omega is a marker
< Learned rule: marker(X) :- xchi(X), psi(X), omega(X).
> every red blue green is a marker
< Learned rule: marker(X) :- red(X), blue(X), green(X).
> every shortcut token is a marker
< Learned rule: marker(X) :- shortcut(X), token(X).
> zed is token
< Learned: token(zed).
> what is the easiest way to make zed a marker?
< The easiest way is to tell me that zed is a shortcut — 1 missing premise via shortcut and token -> marker.
> simulate the easiest way to make zed a marker
< Hypothetically adding zed is a shortcut makes zed a marker: marker(zed) because shortcut(zed) and token(zed). I restored the KB after the simulation.
> is zed a marker?
< No.




# Take one branch; the consequence is volunteered (gen103) and the goal holds.
> rex is a cat
< Learned: cat(rex).
> is rex a pet?
< Yes.
